"Yano M., Nagao M., Okamoto K., Tomita A., Uchiyama Y., Uchiyama N., Hibino T.","A single-chamber SOFC stack operating in engine exhaust",2008,"Electrochemical and Solid-State Letters","11","3",,"B29","B33",,,10.1149/1.2824502,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-38349167021&partnerID=40&md5=ec8530acfbfa0a1d4a5d3c00bb033990","Graduate School of Environmental Studies, Nagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan; National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology, Materials Research Institute for Sustainable Development, Nagoya 463-8560, Japan; AtsumiTec Company, Limited, Hamamatsu-shi, Shizuoka 431-0192, Japan; Electrochemical Society","Yano, M., Graduate School of Environmental Studies, Nagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan; Nagao, M., Graduate School of Environmental Studies, Nagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan, Electrochemical Society; Okamoto, K., Graduate School of Environmental Studies, Nagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan; Tomita, A., National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology, Materials Research Institute for Sustainable Development, Nagoya 463-8560, Japan; Uchiyama, Y., AtsumiTec Company, Limited, Hamamatsu-shi, Shizuoka 431-0192, Japan; Uchiyama, N., AtsumiTec Company, Limited, Hamamatsu-shi, Shizuoka 431-0192, Japan; Hibino, T., Graduate School of Environmental Studies, Nagoya University, Nagoya 464-8601, Japan, Electrochemical Society","Heat engines emit huge amounts of exhaust which contain considerable quantities of heat and chemical energies. An increasing public awareness of global warming and oil depletion has required the development of innovative methods of recovering energy from such exhaust. A promising approach is to produce electricity from unburned fuel by using a fuel cell system. The exhaust includes cracked-light hydrocarbons, offering the possibility of applying this system to a power generator. Solid oxide fuel cells (SOFCs) can work at elevated temperatures but have poor thermal and mechanical shock resistance. In this study, we address this problem by operating the fuel cell system in a single-chamber mode, wherein no separation between fuel and oxidant gases is required. This operation provides high tolerance toward thermal cycling and breakage of the electrolyte. As a result, a twelve-cell stack exhibits stable and high performance in the exhaust from a motorcycle. © 2007 The Electrochemical Society.",,"Global warming; Heat engines; Heat resistance; Hydrocarbons; Shock problems; Solid oxide fuel cells (SOFC); Thermal cycling; Energy recovery; Mechanical shock resistance; Oil depletion; Exhaust systems (engine)",,,,,,"Steele, B.C.H., Heinzel, A., (2001) Nature (London), 414, p. 345. , NATUAS 0028-0836 10.1038/35104620; Yano, M., Tomita, A., Sano, M., Hibino, T., (2007) Solid State Ionics, 177, p. 3351. , SSIOD3 0167-2738 10.1016/j.ssi.2006.10.014; Hibino, T., Wang, S., Kakimoto, S., Sano, M., (1999) Electrochem. Solid-State Lett., 2, p. 317. , ESLEF6 1099-0062 10.1149/1.1390822; Morel, B., Roberge, R., Savoie, S., Napporn, T.W., Meunier, M., (2007) Appl. Catal., A, 323, p. 181. , ACAGE4 0926-860X; Priestnall, M.A., Kotzeva, V.P., Fish, D.J., Nilsson, E.M., (2002) J. Power Sources, 106, p. 21. , JPSODZ 0378-7753 10.1016/S0378-7753(01)01068-0; Riess, I., (2005) Solid State Ionics, 176, p. 1667. , SSIOD3 0167-2738 10.1016/j.ssi.2005.04.015; Hibino, T., Wang, S., Kakimoto, S., Sano, M., (2000) Solid State Ionics, 127, p. 89. , SSIOD3 0167-2738 10.1016/S0167-2738(99)00253-2; Tomita, A., Hirabayashi, D., Hibino, T., Nagao, N., Sano, M., (2005) Electrochem. Solid-State Lett., 8, p. 63. , ESLEF6 1099-0062 10.1149/1.1836120; Hibino, T., Hashimoto, A., Inoue, T., Tokuno, J., Yoshida, S., Sano, M., (2001) J. Electrochem. Soc., 148, p. 544. , JESOAN 0013-4651 10.1149/1.1368098; Napporn, T.W., Jacques-B́dard, X., Morin, F., Meunier, M., (2004) J. Electrochem. Soc., 151, p. 2088. , JESOAN 0013-4651 10.1149/1.1814034; Suzuki, T., Jasinski, P., Petr